        <name>37.3.3.1 The Poisson Process: Large metal sheets</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Large sheets of metal have faults in random positions but on average have \(1\) fault per \(10\) m&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(^2\)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is the probability that a sheet {@sheet@}&amp;nbsp;m\(^2\) will have at most one fault?&lt;/p&gt;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Poisson Process. In a sheet size {@sheet@} \(m^2\) &lt;strong&gt;we expect&lt;/strong&gt; {@faults@} faults, therefore \(\lambda = \text{E}(X) = {@faults@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Recall that the Poisson mass function is \(\text{P}(X=r) = \lambda^r e^{-\lambda}/r!\) for \(r = 0,1,2,\ldots\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, \(\text{P}(X\le 1) = \text{P}(X=0) + \text{P}(X=1) = {@decimalplaces(prob0, 4)@} + {@decimalplaces(prob1, 4)@} = {@tans1@}\) to 4 decimal places.&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
